</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A function <fr:tex>f \colon  A  \to  B</fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when all of its <fr:link
href="erct-001Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001Q">fibers</fr:link> are <fr:link
href="erct-001G.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001G"><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span> types</fr:link>. By analogy, we shall also refer to maps as <fr:em><fr:strong>contractible</fr:strong></fr:em> when their fibers are; we shall refer to maps as <fr:em><fr:strong>propositional</fr:strong></fr:em> when their fibers are <fr:link
href="erct-001I.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001I">propositions</fr:link>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
